  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Road Returning from Shu to Yan
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Upon my horse I hum the melodies of Shu's distant roads.
    This dawn I pass once more through the Qin Gate.
    As twilight falls, blue clouds veil the Fisher's Stream,
    and autumn's crimson trees line the Bird-Mouse Mountains.

    The written word compounds a thousand years of sorrow,
    yet who can claim both fame and a carefree heart?

    Oh, how I long for that pleasant path ahead—
    where once in sandals and with bamboo staff,
    I wandered freely, coming and going as I pleased.
  footnotes:
    - The poem references Li Bai's famous work 'The Difficulty of the Shu Road,' establishing a dialogue with classical literature about arduous journeys.
    - The Qin Gate marks the boundary between ancient Shu (modern Sichuan) and Yan (modern Beijing region), representing the poet's passage from one realm to another.
    - The Fisher's Stream and Bird-Mouse Mountains are specific geographical landmarks along the historical route, grounding the journey in concrete reality.
    - The contrast between the driven pursuit of 'fame and profit' and the remembered simplicity of wandering with only a bamboo staff and straw sandals reflects a deep philosophical tension in the poet's heart.
